==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Synchronize
<hw>Syn"chro*nize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Synchronized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Synchronizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph>
<ety>[Gr. <?/.]</ety> <def>To agree in time; to be
simultaneous.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The path of this great empire, through its arch of progress,
<qex>synchronized</qex> with that of Christianity.</q> <rj><qau>De
Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Synchronize</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Synchronize
<hw>Syn"chro*nize</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To assign to
the same date or period of time; <as>as, to <ex>synchronize</ex> two
events of Greek and Roman history</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Josephus
<xex>synchronizes</xex> Nisan with the Egyptian Pharmus.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>W. L. Bevan.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to agree in time; <as>as, to
<ex>synchronize</ex> the movements of different machines; to
<ex>synchronize</ex> clocks.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Synchronology</ent>⟦br⟧
